{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὄφις</b>, ὁ, <br /> <i>genitive</i> ὄφεως, <i>poetry</i> also ὄφεος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Supplices” 703, “Ba.” 1026, 1331 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> and <i>Ionic dialect</i> ὄφιος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 322, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.81, 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 82 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>serpent</b>, αἰόλος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.208; γλαυκῶπα ποικιλόνωτον ὄφιν 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 4.249, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 544, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1328, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.41, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 112d, “R.” 358b, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ ψυχρὸς ὄ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 15.58 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; equivalent to δράκων in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 322, 825: _metaphorically_, πτηνὸν ἀργηστὴν ὄφιν, of an arrow, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 181. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> like{δράκων}, <b>a serpent-like bracelet</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 387, 4th c.BC: Nicostratus Philosophus Comedy texts 33, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Epistulae” 22 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὄφεις is <i>Attic dialect</i> for ψέλλια <i>accusative</i> to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Moeris Grammaticus p.288 P. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> τρικάρηνος ὄ. ὁ χάλκεος dedicated at Delphi (= [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 31), 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.81. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> the constellation [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Serpens”, 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 82, 4th c.BC: Eudoxus Astronomus cited in 2nd c.BC: Hipparchus Astronomicus 1.2.18. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>a creeping plant</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “γυναικεῖα” 2.114. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> a kind of <b>fish</b>, see at {ὀφίδιον} [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VI</b></Level2> <b>guinea-worm</b> (elsewhere δρακόντιον), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Rufus Medicus “Interrog.” 65. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__VII</b></Level2> ={ὀφίασις} I, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD: Celsus Medicus 6.4, 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 4.192 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]. [The first syllable is sometimes made long in the older Poets, αἰόλον ὄφιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.208, compare 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 49.6; so ὀφιοέσσης 5th-6th c.BC: Antimachus Colophonius Elegiacus et Epicus 78. It was then pronounced (and perhaps written) ὄπφις, ὀπφιοέσσης, see Eust. 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” [same place] \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —The <i>ultima </i> of the _nominative_ and _accusative_ ὄφις, ὄφιν is commonly long, as in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 334, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 928, 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 2.1269, 2nd c.BC: Moschus Bucolicus 4.22 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; short only in later Poets, as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Apollonius Rhodius Epicus 4.128, 1398, 4th-3rd c.BC: Aratus Epicus 578.] \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3789","accentedUnicode":"ὄφις","shortDef":"snake, serpent","mediumDef":"snake, serpent <br /><b>a serpent,</b> <ref='Mat.7.10; 10:16'>Mt. 7:10; 10:16</ref>; <b>an</b> artificial <b>serpent,</b> <ref='Jhn.3.14'>Jn. 3:14</ref>; used of <b>the devil</b> or <b>Satan,</b> <ref='Rev.12.9, 14, 15; 20.2'>Rev. 12:9, 14, 15; 20:2</ref>; <i>metaphorically</i> <b>a man of serpentine character,</b> <ref='Mat.23.33'>Mt. 23:33</ref>","stepGloss":"snake","stepTransliteration":"ofis","count":14,"_es_Definition":"culebra, serpiente","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 蛇<br>2) 危險人物 (太 23:33)<br>3) (通常在神話中的象徵角色) 蛇","_zh_Definition":"1) 蛇<br>2) 危险人物 (太 23:33)<br>3) (通常在神话中的象征角色) 蛇","_step_Type":"word","_vi_Definition":"con rắn","_zh_tw_Gloss":"蛇","_es_Gloss":"culebra","_zh_Gloss":"蛇"}]}